{"key":"processedPost-6260878","value":{"id":6260878,"first":6260311,"last":6261890,"when":1163000262,"utime":"11/08/06 05:37 PM","content":"Horse manure is better for its texture, even though steer manure is higher in nutrition such as nitrogen.  Mycelium easily penetrates horse manure, while cow manure can pack down tight and become harder to colonize.<br /><br />Composted cow manure from nurseries works fine if you lay it out on a tarp in the sun for a few days to burn the ammonia off.  When you prepare it, mix with up to 40% vermiculite to prevent clumping. Coir can be substituted for the verm.  It also helps to add coffee grinds from your morning pot of coffee if you have them.<br />RR","title":"Re: Why hpoo instead of cow poo?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}